Confluence is able to search for a specific user with the specific username by using the search syntax:

{code}
username:
{code}

But this is not documented from this documentation page:
https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence+Search+Fields

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-36697].
  {panel}

A customer has requested that attachments that share the same name, but differing in suffix (e.g. doc vs docx, xls vs xlsx) to be treated as the same file for purposes of maintaining version history.

Quoting use case from the customer:
{quote}
We have upgraded our Word version so that now the default suffix is .docx. When a user tried to version up a document with a .doc suffix, Word saves it as docx. 

The problem comes in when we try to upload to Confluence as an updated version--Confluence adds the document to the page as a different document. 

Even though the file names are the same, Confluence sees the file names as different because of the suffix.
{quote}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-36690].
  {panel}

After a migration from Cloud to Standalone, Confluence will have the default "sysadmin" user included in the user database.

_Confluence needs to notify the user that's it's safe to modify/disable "sysadmin"_ (as long as there's at least 1 user with System Administrator privilege in the system).

'sysadmin' is counted toward Confluence License and sometimes user is not aware that it's safe to modify or disable this user to reduce the license count. Some users might think that 'sysadmin' is like a 'root' user that's not supposed to be touched to avoid issue with the system.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-36685].
  {panel}

Confluence 5.7 introduced inline commenting, which is great. It would be even better if these comments could be made while editing the page.

Another thing I noticed is that when I am editing a page and at the same time add a comment (in the read mode) that does not affect the comment I have edited, when saving the page, I am prompted to override the changes, which will remove my comment. So that's another reason for having inline comments in the edit mode.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-36682].
  {panel}

When a Confluence DC node panics, it doesn't log the cluster safety number it used to make that decision, which is very annoying.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-36676].
