  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-36579].
  {panel}

*Global Stylesheet* CSS will not be applied if *Space Stylesheet* contains any CSS or code in it.

h3. How to Reproduce
# Create a Confluence page using the following Storage Format with *Confluence Source Editor*.
{code}<div class="test1">
  <p>This is a sentence.</p>
</div>
{code}
# Apply the following CSS at *Global Stylesheet* via *Confluence Administration Console* > *Stylesheet*.
{code} .test1  
{  
color: blue;  
}  {code}
# Refresh Confluence page and see the contents colour turn *blue*.
# Apply the following CSS at *Space Stylesheet* via *Space tools* > *Look and Feel* > *Stylesheet*.
{code}.sample
{
color: red;
}
{code}
# Refresh Confluence page again and observe the contents colour change.

h3. Actual Behaviour
Contents colour will change to black (original colour as if there are no CSS defined).

h6. Note
Space defined CSS should add style on top of global defined CSS instead of overwriting it.

